	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Jarhmander</b> [ Fri Sep 09, 2011 2:35 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I would never rely on that 'AND' logic to be the correct implementation of a bus confilct... If the EPROM has higher impedence outputs, it could happen that the CPU always "win" the battle, or on the other side if you place an EPROM with lower impedence it could either "win" the battle against the CPU or cause the power supply to fail and the NES to reset itself.<br />It's not a surprise the transistor driving the line low typically "wins" the battle, but nobody should rely on this.</div>
<br />The 2A03 is NMOS technology, which mean logical one is driven by depletion-mode N-channel FETs used as constant current source. If the 2A03 outputs a logical one and the ROM (or something else) shorts it to ground, then you can always expect that the result is logical zero. The reverse is not necessarily true, though.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
